A '''Boston accent''' is a [[regional accent|local accent]] of [[Eastern New England English]] native specifically to the city of [[Boston]] and its suburbs. Eastern New England English also traditionally includes New Hampshire, Maine, all of eastern Massachusetts, and arguably Rhode Island, though some uniquely local vocabulary appears only around Boston.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Schneider | first = Edgar |author2=Bernd Kortmann | title = A Handbook of Varieties of English: A Multi-Media Reference Tool | publisher = Mouton de Gruyter | year = 2005 | page = 270 | isbn = 978-3-11-017532-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Millward | first = C.M. | title = A Biography of the English Language | publisher = Wadsworth Publishing | year = 1996 | page = 353 | isbn = 978-0-15-501645-3}}</ref> Some of the characteristics of traditional Boston accents may be retreating, particularly among younger residents. However, linguist [[William Labov]] claims that, in the twenty-first century, there remains a relatively stable Boston accent.<ref name="Labov 2010">Labov, William (2010). ''[http://www.cogsci.msu.edu/DSS/2011-2012/Labov/POLC%20Chapters%201-3.pdf The Politics of Language Change: Dialect Divergence in America]''. The University of Virginia Press. Pre-publication draft. p. 53.</ref>

