Boston and surrounding northeastern [[New England]] form the only major region in North America where the [[Phonological history of the low back vowels|distinction between the vowel phonemes]] "broad ''a''" (as in ''father'') and "short ''o''" (as in ''bother'') is often maintained (with some [[New York accent]]s also following this pattern).<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=235}}</ref> Examples include words like ''father'' and ''spa'' which contain {{IPA|[aː]}} ({{IPA|[ˈfaːðə]}}, {{IPA|[spaː]}}) and ''bother'' and ''dock'' which contain {{IPA|[ɒː]}} ({{IPA|[ˈbɒːðə]}}, {{IPA|[dɒːk]}}) being different. This means that even though ''dark'' has no {{IPA|[ɹ]}} in many Boston accents, it remains distinct from ''dock'' because its vowel quality is different: {{IPA|[daːk]}} vs. {{IPA|[dɒːk]}}. In this way, Bostonians align with most Britons, but unlike most other Americans, who use the same vowel in both of these classes: {{IPA|[ɑː]}}.<ref>Labov et al. 2006 The Atlas of North American English Berlin: DeGruyter</ref>{{pn|date=July 2018}}

On the other hand, the Boston accent merges the "short ''o''" with the "aw" phoneme: the two classes exemplified by [[Cot–caught merger|''caught'' and ''cot'']] thus both become an often long and rounded {{IPA|[ɒː]}}, so that ''caught'', ''cot'', ''law'', ''wand'', ''rock'', ''talk'', ''doll'', and ''wall'' all are pronounced with the same vowel.<ref>Labov et al. (2006), pp. 60-1.</ref> By contrast, New York accents and southern New England accents have {{IPA|[kɔət]}} for ''caught'' and {{IPA|[kät]}} for ''cot'' and the London accents have {{IPA|[kɔːt~koːt]}} and {{IPA|[kɒt~kɔt]}}, respectively.  In Boston and some other parts of New England, a few words ending in {{IPA|/t/}}, e.g., ''hot'' and ''got'', can be pronounced with an entirely different phoneme, however, sounding instead like ''hut'' and ''gut'', respectively.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}

Eastern New England English has a so-called "[[Æ-tensing|nasal short-''a'' system]]". This means that the "short ''a''" vowel {{IPA|[æ]}} as in ''cat'' and ''rat'' becomes raised to a mid-high front diphthong {{IPA|[eə]}} when it precedes a [[nasal stop|nasal consonant]] (but also, on a continuous scale in some other environments); thus, ''man'' is {{IPA|[meən]}} and ''planet'' is {{IPA|[ˈpleənət]}}. Boston shares this system with some of the Midwest and most of the West, though the raising in Boston tends to be more noticeable and extreme than elsewhere. This system is not shared with London or New York City accents. In addition to raising before nasals, Bostonians (unlike nearby New Hampshirites, for example) also tend to somewhat "raise" or "break" the "short ''a''" sound the most before [[voiceless fricative]]s (followed by [[voiced stop]]s, laterals, voiceless stops, and voiced fricatives), so that words like ''half'', ''bath'', and ''glass'' become {{IPA|[hɛəf]}}, {{IPA|[bɛəθ]}} and {{IPA|[glɛəs]}}, respectively.<ref>Wood, Jim. (2010). "[https://jimwood8.files.wordpress.com/2018/06/wood-2011-short-a-in-northern-new-england.pdf Short-a in Northern New England]". ''Journal of English Linguistics'' 20:1–31. pp. 146, 149.</ref> This trend began around the early-mid to mid-twentieth century, replacing the older Boston accent's London-like "broad ''a''" system to an opener {{IPA|[a]}} sound in those same example words (see "Declining characteristics" below).<ref>Wood, 2010, p. 139.</ref>

