{{Orphan|date=June 2015}}

[[File:1724 De L'Isle Map of Persia (Iran, Iraq, Afghanistan) - Geographicus - Persia-delisle-1724.jpg|thumb|Right|Map of Persia 1724]]'''Gulashkird''' also known as Faryjab or Paryjab or Valashgird<ref>Lewis Vance Cummings, Alexander the Great (Grove Press, 2004)[https://books.google.com/books?id=D5PQBWYmXgkC&pg=PA402&lpg=PA402&dq=Gulashkird&source=bl&ots=psPuav15aH&sig=RgLyGYWAcliSFqB814pYXUNdKSM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JcmCVcWBLIvk8AXuyIPIBQ&ved=0CCoQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Gulashkird&f=false page 402].</ref> was an important town in [[Kerman provence]] of [[Iran]] during the [[Medieval|Middle Ages]] as a station on the [[silk road|trade routes]] from The [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Persia]] to [[India]] and also into [[Central Asia]].<ref>E. H. Warmington, The Commerce Between the [[Roman Empire]] and [[India]] ([[Cambridge University Press|CUP]] Archive, 2014) [https://books.google.com/books?id=u9w8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=Gulashkird&source=bl&ots=I0Y4WfZDg2&sig=hBNDeTLdXjfigxWVh-4MgIKut0A&hl=en&sa=X&ei=SMiCVer8MdLz8gXugbUg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Gulashkird&f=false   page 24].</ref>

Today the town lies at modern [[Faryab, Iran|Faryjab]], a small village north east of [[Bandar Abbas]], south of [[Jiroft]] and 50&nbsp;km north of Mantijan, near the town of Manujan and the [[Rudkhanah-i-Duzdi|Rudkhanah i Duzdi River]].

Historically the town was a strongly fortified town with a castle known as Kftshah and was serviced by [[quanat]]s that allowed the area to grow [[Indigo]],<ref>[http://www.forgottenbooks.com/readbook_text/The_Lands_of_the_Eastern_Caliphate_1000703829/345 Lands of the Eastern Caliphate].</ref> [[Orange (fruit)|Orange]]s and [[Date Palm]]s<ref>[[Guy Le Strange]], The Lands of the Eastern Caliphate: Mesopotamia, Persia, and Central Asia from the Moslem Conquest to the Time of Timur (Cosimo, Inc., 2010)[https://books.google.com/books?id=vCyL06XqE18C&pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=Valashgird&source=bl&ots=iAOZIWZUUM&sig=j3xQPa3wJiq5qriWwoqDlF_eVQY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-jqDVeq4EMO7mgXnhLCQDg&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=Valashgird&f=false  page 318].</ref> and Grain<ref>E. Yarshater, ''The Cambridge History of Iran: Seleucid Parthian'' ([[Cambridge University Press]], 1983) [https://books.google.com/books?id=y7IHmyKcPtYC&pg=PA773&lpg=PA773&dq=Valashgird&source=bl&ots=3VsKO8TfgA&sig=BNhNlf17lCfw7Fyx8WE8ELX0J1k&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mjyDVcrzNMi5mAXWioLACQ&ved=0CC4Q6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Valashgird&f=false pazge 173].</ref> It was mentioned by [[Arab geographer]]s [[Al-Muqaddasi|Mukaddasi]] and [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]]<ref>Yakut (iv, 939)</ref> and [[Marco Polo]].<ref>[http://www.bookrags.com/ebooks/12410/630.html Travels of Marco Polo Vol2].</ref><ref>The travels of Marco Polo vol 1, chapter16.</ref>

The village has been suggested<ref>G. Le Strange, The Lands of the Eastern Caliphate, [[Cambridge University Press]] 2011. [https://books.google.com/books?id=UJqxGH_QuXcC&pg=PA317&lpg=PA317&dq=Valashgird&source=bl&ots=m8cJOShZUA&sig=r8cWmAg6ngAUZoVQbauR8Yy7iV8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=91GlUbPyGI2mkgXWvIHYCw&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Valashgird&f=false   page 317]</ref> as a possible location for the lost city of [[Alexandria Carmania]], founded by [[Alexander the Great]] months before he died in [[Babylon]].<ref>[[Lewis Vance Cummings]], [[Alexander the Great]] (Grove Press, 2004)[https://books.google.com/books?id=D5PQBWYmXgkC&pg=PA402&lpg=PA402&dq=Gulashkird&source=bl&ots=psPuav15aH&sig=RgLyGYWAcliSFqB814pYXUNdKSM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JcmCVcWBLIvk8AXuyIPIBQ&ved=0CCoQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Gulashkird&f=false page 402] p402</ref> Indeed, [[ancient greek|Greek]] [[pottery#Archaeology|pottery]] has been found in the area.<ref>[[Percy Sykes|Sir Percy Molesworth Sykes]], A History of Exploration from the Earliest Times to the Present Day, Taylor & Francis, 1949</ref>

